            <fr:title text="dense subsite">dense subsite</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Given a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001A/" title="Grothendieck coverage" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001A/" display-uri="algm-001A" type="local">Grothendieck coverage</fr:link> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>, we can induce a coverage on any subcategory <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {D}]]></fr:tex> by restricting the covering sieves to the subcategory. It is <html:strong>dense</html:strong> iff every object in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> can be covered by morphisms from objects in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {D}]]></fr:tex>, and for every morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : X \to  Y]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X, Y]]></fr:tex> are in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {D}]]></fr:tex>, we can cover <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {D}]]></fr:tex> such that the compositions with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> are still in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {D}]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  We can define sheaves on dense subsites, and they uniquely extend to the entire site. This induces an equivalence of sheaf categories. For locales with the canonical coverage, full dense subsites are exactly topological bases.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>7</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001U/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>algm-001U</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/forest/algm-001U/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="slice of sheaf category">slice of sheaf category</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Construction</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  Given a category <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> with a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001A/" title="Grothendieck coverage" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001A/" display-uri="algm-001A" type="local">Grothendieck coverage</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> and a sheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>, there is a Grothendieck coverage <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J']]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\int _{\mathcal {C}} F]]></fr:tex> such that the equivalence in <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001T/" title="slice of presheaf category" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001T/" display-uri="algm-001T" type="local">Theorem <fr:contextual-number uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001T/" display-uri="algm-001T" /></fr:link> restricts to an equivalence
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\mathsf {Sh}(\mathcal {C}, J)/F \cong  \mathsf {Sh}\left (\int _{\mathcal {C}} F, J'\right ).]]></fr:tex></html:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>7</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    Suppose we have a covering sieve <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S \hookrightarrow  \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U)]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex>, then an element <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f \in  \Gamma (U, F)]]></fr:tex> uniquely corresponds to a matching family <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s \in  \hom (S, F)]]></fr:tex>. In the category of elements <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\int _{\mathcal {C}} F]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex> corresponds to a sieve over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>. This is the required Grothendieck coverage.
  </html:p>

  <html:p>
    Another way to construct this is through the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001L/" title="Lawvere–Tierney operator" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001L/" display-uri="algm-001L" type="local">Lawvere–Tierney operator</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>. The subobject classifier of a slice category is simply <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega  \times  F \to  F]]></fr:tex>. Hence we can let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex> act on the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> factor. This gives a Lawvere–Tierney operator on the slice category and it coincides with the Grothendieck coverage constructed above.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>5</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001P/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>algm-001P</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/forest/algm-001P/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="sheaf condition using Lawvere–Tierney operators">sheaf condition using Lawvere–Tierney operators</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Knowing the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001N/" title="Grothendieck coverages and Lawvere–Tierney operators" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001N/" display-uri="algm-001N" type="local">correspondence</fr:link> of Grothendieck coverages on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> and Lawvere–Tierney operators on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {Psh}(\mathcal {C})]]></fr:tex>, we naturally want to rewrite the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001F/" title="sheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001F/" display-uri="algm-001F" type="local">sheaf condition</fr:link> to use <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001L/" title="Lawvere–Tierney operator" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001L/" display-uri="algm-001L" type="local">Lawvere–Tierney operators</fr:link> instead of <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001A/" title="Grothendieck coverage" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001A/" display-uri="algm-001A" type="local">Grothendieck coverages</fr:link>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  Recall that the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001F/" title="sheaf" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001F/" display-uri="algm-001F" type="local">sheaf condition</fr:link> requires for every covering sieve <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S \hookrightarrow  \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U)]]></fr:tex> that the composition <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\hom (\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U), X) \to  \hom (S, X)]]></fr:tex> is an isomorphism. We can reify this to a definition.
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>5</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001R/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>algm-001R</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/forest/algm-001R/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="local object">local object</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  Given a class of arrows <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>-<html:strong>local object</html:strong> is an object <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> such that for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : A \to  B]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, the composition map <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\hom (B, X) \to  \hom (A, X)]]></fr:tex> is an isomorphism.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>
  Now we just need to pick out the class of morphisms <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S \hookrightarrow  \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U)]]></fr:tex> using the Lawvere–Tierney operator <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>. Note that this operator does not necessarily live in a presheaf topos, so we must find a way to generalize this class of arrows to not necessarily representable presheaves. Since every presheaf is a colimit of representables, we can look at the corresponding colimit of morphisms <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname *{colim} S_i \hookrightarrow  \operatorname *{colim} \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U_i)]]></fr:tex>. A local object will satisfy
  <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {aligned}
    \hom (\operatorname *{colim}\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U_i), X) \cong  \lim \hom (\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U_i), X) \quad  \\
    \xrightarrow {\sim } \lim \hom (S_i, X) \cong  \hom (\operatorname *{colim} S_i, X).
  \end {aligned}]]></fr:tex>
  Hence we can safely include these arrows into the class and still get the same concept of local objects. Now it’s illuminating to look at the characteristic maps. A sieve <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S \to  \mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U)]]></fr:tex> corresponds to a characteristic map in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\hom (\mathop {\mkern {-2mu}\text {よ}\mkern {-2mu}}(U), \Omega ) \cong  \Gamma (U, \Omega )]]></fr:tex>. Generalizing to an arbitrary presheaf expressed (canonically) as a colimit of representables, we need the image of every section to be a covering sieve.
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>5</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001Q/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>algm-001Q</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/forest/algm-001Q/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="dense subobject of a Lawvere–Tierney operator">dense subobject of a Lawvere–Tierney operator</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  Given a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001L/" title="Lawvere–Tierney operator" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001L/" display-uri="algm-001L" type="local">Lawvere–Tierney operator</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>, a subobject <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F \hookrightarrow  G]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>-<html:strong>dense</html:strong> if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G \to  \Omega  \xrightarrow {j} \Omega ]]></fr:tex> is the constant true. In terms of the corresponding <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J \hookrightarrow  \Omega ]]></fr:tex>, we need the pullback of it with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G \to  \Omega ]]></fr:tex> to be <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\textrm {id} : G \to  G]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>
  In terms of sieves, for every section <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s \in  \Gamma (U, G)]]></fr:tex>, the sieve of arrows on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> along whom the restriction of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s]]></fr:tex> is in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> must be a covering sieve. We have arrived at the desired reformulation of the sheaf condition.
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>4</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>5</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001S/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>algm-001S</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/forest/algm-001S/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="sheaf of a Lawvere–Tierney operator">sheaf of a Lawvere–Tierney operator</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  Given a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001L/" title="Lawvere–Tierney operator" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001L/" display-uri="algm-001L" type="local">Lawvere–Tierney operator</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>, a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>-<html:strong>sheaf</html:strong> is defined as a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>-<html:strong>local object</html:strong>, i.e. a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001R/" title="local object" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001R/" display-uri="algm-001R" type="local">local object</fr:link> under the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001Q/" title="dense subobject of a Lawvere–Tierney operator" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001Q/" display-uri="algm-001Q" type="local"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>-dense monomorphisms</fr:link>.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
              <fr:month>4</fr:month>
              <fr:day>4</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:uri>https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001N/</fr:uri>
            <fr:display-uri>algm-001N</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/forest/algm-001N/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Grothendieck coverages and Lawvere–Tierney operators">Grothendieck coverages and Lawvere–Tierney operators</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Consider a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001L/" title="Lawvere–Tierney operator" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001L/" display-uri="algm-001L" type="local">Lawvere–Tierney operator</fr:link> on a presheaf category. Then we may calculate the subobject classifier as in <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001M/" title="subobject classifier of presheaves" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001M/" display-uri="algm-001M" type="local">Construction <fr:contextual-number uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001M/" display-uri="algm-001M" /></fr:link>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  By the definition of subobject classifiers, a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001L/" title="Lawvere–Tierney operator" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001L/" display-uri="algm-001L" type="local">Lawvere–Tierney operator</fr:link> can be equivalently expressed as a subobject <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J \subseteq  \Omega ]]></fr:tex>. Translating the condition of preserving finite intersections, it needs to contain the improper sieve, be upwards closed and closed under finite intersections. And <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j \mathbin {\circ } j = j]]></fr:tex> implies the following pullback square:
  
  <html:span class="tikz tikzcd">
    <fr:resource hash="2b9c8ac34ee25178be732342bce3fa0f"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/forest/2b9c8ac34ee25178be732342bce3fa0f.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[
            \usepackage{mlmodern, tikz, tikz-cd, quiver, mathtools, amssymb, stmaryrd, mathrsfs}
    ]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
      \begin {tikzcd}%tex
    J & J \\
    \Omega & \Omega
    \arrow[hook, from=1-2, to=2-2]
    \arrow["j"', from=2-1, to=2-2]
    \arrow[hook, from=1-1, to=2-1]
    \arrow[from=1-1, to=1-2]
    \arrow["\lrcorner"{anchor=center, pos=0.125}, draw=none, from=1-1, to=2-2]\end {tikzcd}
    ]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource>
  </html:span>

  In other words, a sieve is contained in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> iff its image under <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex> is also contained in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex>. Unfolding this, a sieve <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is contained in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> iff the arrows <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g^* S]]></fr:tex> is contained in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> also form a sieve in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex>. Looking at the definition of a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001A/" title="Grothendieck coverage" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001A/" display-uri="algm-001A" type="local">Grothendieck coverage</fr:link>, we see that they are equivalent, if we regard <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex> as picking out the covering sieves.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  In the operator form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex>, it takes in a sieve <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> and outputs the sieve <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j(S)]]></fr:tex> consisting of all the subobjects <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> can cover, or equivalently it outputs the largest sieve that covers the “same portion” of the object.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
