            <fr:title text="plus construction">plus construction</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Given a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001A/" title="Grothendieck coverage" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001A/" display-uri="algm-001A" type="local">Grothendieck coverage</fr:link> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {C}]]></fr:tex> and a presheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P : \mathcal {C}^\textrm {op} \to  \mathsf {Set}]]></fr:tex>, the <html:strong>plus construction</html:strong> produces a new presheaf <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^+]]></fr:tex> by taking a directed limit over all the <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001D/" title="descent data of presheaves" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001D/" display-uri="algm-001D" type="local">descent data</fr:link>. More precisely, we assign <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\Gamma (A, P^+) = \operatorname *{colim}_{S \text { covers } A} \hom (S, P).]]></fr:tex> This means the sections of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^+]]></fr:tex> are compatible families of sections of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>, and two families are considered equal if they are equal on a common covering subsieve.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  Given a map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g : B \to  A]]></fr:tex>, we have a <fr:link href="/forest/algm-001C/" title="pullback of sieves" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/algm-001C/" display-uri="algm-001C" type="local">pullback</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\hom (S, P) \to  \hom (g^*S, P)]]></fr:tex>. This induces the functorial action of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^+]]></fr:tex>. There is an obvious natural transformation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P \to  P^+]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
